<subSubSection id="11C06696284E157EDEBE459D2B68DE2D" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="A7A2BBF4EDFA2A1526DCF0C39F22568B" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
<taxonomicName id="13D0455BE6C18C684E26508B3E3CAD72" class="Insecta" family="Apoidea" genus="Halictus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Halictus bractealis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bractealis">Halictus bractealis</taxonomicName>
Vachal, 1904. Holotype male (MNHP) from Peru, 
<normalizedToken id="3CCD3437400AE03422BB429B2E0C780C" originalValue="‘Villanota’">'Villanota'</normalizedToken>
[probably lapsus for Vilcanota, in Cuzco, Peru]. Examined through photographs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D98E7B7F1E8D230E0EDCE0716989CB56" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
<taxonomicName id="88CFBD20907490D6BFF9A901158393E0" class="Insecta" family="Apoidea" genus="Halictus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Halictus pyrrhias" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrrhias">Halictus pyrrhias</taxonomicName>
Vachal, 1911. Lectotype female (MNHP) from Peru, Marcapata. Examined through photographs. New synonym.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7F871EA78E952FDA0D2A8CC429AF5E56" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="comments">
<paragraph id="724333DF1DF189D43FAD3FA9DBC6E702" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A1D48B9F36AE2ABFBB891FC6C56C6D84" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
<bibRefCitation id="1739BBC53B1BA9838DB4A3797BEEE738" author="Moure, JS" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" refId="B39" refString="Moure, JS, Hurd, PD, 1987. An annotated catalog of the halictid bees of the western hemisphere (Hymenoptera: Halictidae). Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington DC" title="An annotated catalog of the halictid bees of the western hemisphere (Hymenoptera: Halictidae)." year="1987">Moure and Hurd (1987)</bibRefCitation>
designated the lectotype for 
<taxonomicName id="7F1C03D5AF54AFC92A63489CE2FAE4E6" class="Insecta" family="Apoidea" genus="Halictus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Halictus pyrrhias" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrrhias">
<emphasis id="D857888FF31E1F43E8E33DAAB3987904" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Halictus pyrrhias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and considered both names under 
<taxonomicName id="FE2DF87039B9F4749E6ACB5E14173EFA" authorityName="Eickwort" authorityYear="1969" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Oxystoglossella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oxystoglossella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E0265CF2D5A66923B22AB5687FD8782C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Oxystoglossella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a decision followed by Moure (2007). We examined the photographs of the types from both names (
<normalizedToken id="03D156C52514A09B0E1FE096082EB424" originalValue="Muséum">Museum</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="102F6AAF82E22429393B214AF7A20502" originalValue="d’Histoire">d'Histoire</normalizedToken>
Naturelle, Paris, France) and the specimens belong to the 
<taxonomicName id="F56373CF5C1FEFD68BB2FC55B92BD27C" class="Insecta" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. hestia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hestia">
<emphasis id="147E6D5F8830394F839D2CCD53AB0EA7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">A. hestia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group in 
<taxonomicName id="3AB0C60595E662AA014435A21F15F017" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Apoidea" genus="Augochlora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Augochlora" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="99A0AA73061DB3690A0DF6C1FA85155F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Augochlora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. str. We also consider that the male and female are the same species proposing the synonymy for these names. As discussed herein, this species superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName id="806E6A8716FE42BADB31B1DCAEAA8724" authorityName="Eickwort" authorityYear="1969" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Oxystoglossella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oxystoglossella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="80A0C5FD1D688B1195685E766A29B77B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Oxystoglossella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and shares labral modifications with that subgenus, what justified 
<bibRefCitation id="2176F09B559B1EAAEED76628B8400D36" author="Moure, JS" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" refId="B39" refString="Moure, JS, Hurd, PD, 1987. An annotated catalog of the halictid bees of the western hemisphere (Hymenoptera: Halictidae). Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington DC" title="An annotated catalog of the halictid bees of the western hemisphere (Hymenoptera: Halictidae)." year="1987">
Moure and 
<normalizedToken id="15899A900C16E165CAEE531BD2557832" originalValue="Hurd’s">Hurd's</normalizedToken>
(1987)
</bibRefCitation>
generic assignment.
</paragraph>
